<br>
I treat my potions like I would a business.  It makes no sense to level up your skill, especially when I started, with the minus stat potions, then give away your wares.<br>
<br>
In my above-listed chart, I take into account Research and Development, i.e. FAILURES, and skill ups into my pricing.  I have options for higher costing items (thus lower mark-ups).<br>
<br>
Remember, you spent outrageous sums of money building up your skills.  When a pharm company charges you $200.00 for a bottle of pills, you are not only paying for the ingredients, but for the research, testing etc.<br>
<br>
So, in my pricing guide, I price it out this way:<br>
Materials for 13 potions X Mark-up.  Why 13?  I felt that was a good average to compensate for failures on combines.  Sure, my Shaman can make 40 SOW on 43 tries.....NOW, but in the past, I would have around 5-7 failures on ten tries.  PLUS, in the days of MINUS stats, I had tons of potions I had to sell back to vendors at a HUGE HUGE loss.<br>
<br>
I feel my guide is fair to the consumer, and the seller, and undercuts nobody.  So, you are making 5K a week selling undercutted potions?  I guess you are not taking into account the TIME it takes to make those potions.  If you are making 5K a week selling bargain potions, you could be making 3 times that amount by actually hunting things in the time it takes you to make potions.<br>
<br>
So, you see yourself making 5K a week?  I see you losing 10K a week, by selling bargain basement items.  It is just the way you look at things.  Do you open a shop and decide to sell things at a loss for 3 years to make a profit for 2?<br>
<br>
If you have two jobs at 20 hours each, and one pays you $500.00 for 20 hours, and the other pays you $1000.00 for 20 hours, well, job one is COSTING you $500.00 a week.  <br>
<br>
If you did NOT undercut the competition, your 5K a week MIGHT get you the 10K that you would make by hunting.<br>
